SIMPLE: pretty
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pretty
<hw>Pret"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Prettier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Prettiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>prati</ets>, AS.
<ets>pr⟦ae⟧ttig</ets>, <ets>pr⟦ae⟧tig</ets>, crafty, sly, akin to
<ets>pr⟦ae⟧t</ets>, <ets>pr⟦ae⟧tt</ets>, deceit, trickery, Icel.
<ets>prettugr</ets> tricky, <ets>prettr</ets> a trick; probably fr.
Latin, perhaps through Celtic; cf. W. <ets>praith</ets> act, deed,
practice, LL. <ets>practica</ets> execution, practice, plot. See
<er>Practice</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pleasing by delicacy or
grace; attracting, but not striking or impressing; of a pleasing and
attractive form a color; having slight or diminutive beauty; neat or
elegant without elevation or grandeur; pleasingly, but not grandly,
conceived or expressed; <as>as, a <ex>pretty</ex> face; a
<ex>pretty</ex> flower; a <ex>pretty</ex> poem.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the <qex>prettiest</qex> lowborn lass that ever⟦br⟧
Ran on the greensward.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Moderately large; considerable; <as>as, he had saved
a <ex>pretty</ex> fortune</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Wavering a
<xex>pretty</xex> while.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Affectedly nice; foppish; -- used in an ill
sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>pretty</qex> gentleman is the most complaisant in the
world.</q> <rj><qau>Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Mean; despicable; contemptible; -- used ironically;
<as>as, a <ex>pretty</ex> trick; a <ex>pretty</ex>
fellow.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Stout; strong and brave; intrepid; valiant.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] observed they were <qex>pretty</qex> men, meaning not
handsome.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Elegant; neat; fine. See
<er>Handsome</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pretty</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pretty
<hw>Pret"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In some degree;
moderately; considerably; rather; almost; -- less emphatic than
<xex>very</xex>; <as>as, I am <ex>pretty</ex> sure of the fact;
<ex>pretty</ex> cold weather.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Pretty</qex> plainly professes himself a sincere
Christian.</q> <rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prettyish</ent>⟦br⟧
